{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569019"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:24:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:24:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21651"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21651"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.18,0.1,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103300"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14520"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21651"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85719"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"503"},{"type":"tags","id":"8014"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"36631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103300"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice about discoloured areas on her left leg that appeared approximately six months ago and have gradually increased in size (Image). She is asymptomatic but is concerned because a friend with similar appearance had treatment for varicose veins. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She works as a store manager, does not smoke, and drinks several glasses of wine on weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 28 kg/m\u00b2. The left leg shows small areas of telangiectasia as visible in the image. The right leg has some small varicosities. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice to give this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and lifestyle advice","Duplex ultrasonography","Sclerotherapy","Laser therapy","Endovenous ablation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with asymptomatic telangiectasia on her left leg. Telangiectasias are small dilated blood vessels near the surface of the skin that appear as fine red lines. They are generally benign and do not typically cause symptoms or complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and lifestyle advice\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. Since she is asymptomatic and the telangiectasia are primarily a cosmetic concern, invasive treatments are not necessary. Lifestyle modifications that may help prevent progression include weight loss (her BMI of 28 kg/m\u00b2 indicates she is overweight), regular exercise, avoiding prolonged standing, elevating the legs when possible, and potentially wearing compression stockings. These measures can improve venous return and reduce venous pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuplex ultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were concerns about underlying venous insufficiency causing symptoms such as pain, swelling, aching, or itching. Since this patient is asymptomatic, this investigation is not necessary at this stage. If she were to develop symptoms in the future, duplex ultrasonography would be appropriate to assess venous reflux and plan treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESclerotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E involves injecting a solution into the affected vessels to cause them to collapse and eventually fade. While effective for telangiectasia, this treatment is typically reserved for patients who are bothered by the cosmetic appearance or who have symptoms. Given this patient\u0027s lack of symptoms, sclerotherapy would be an unnecessary intervention with potential risks including pain, inflammation, and pigmentation changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is another treatment option for telangiectasia that works by delivering light energy to the targeted vessels, causing them to collapse. Like sclerotherapy, it is primarily used for cosmetic concerns or symptomatic cases. Since this patient is asymptomatic, laser therapy would be an unnecessary intervention with potential side effects including temporary redness, swelling, and rarely, scarring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndovenous ablation\u003C/strong\u003E techniques (such as radiofrequency or laser ablation) are used to treat larger varicose veins and underlying venous reflux, not telangiectasia. These procedures are more invasive and would be inappropriate for this patient\u0027s presentation. They are typically reserved for patients with symptomatic varicose veins and evidence of significant venous reflux on duplex ultrasonography.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Telangiectasia are small dilated blood vessels near the skin surface that are benign and typically asymptomatic.","Conservative management with lifestyle modifications is appropriate for asymptomatic telangiectasia.","Invasive treatments for telangiectasia should be reserved for patients with symptoms or cosmetic concerns that impact quality of life."],"references":["Goodman EA, Alexander JT, Babrowski TA. Care of Patients With Chronic Venous Disease of the Legs. JAMA 2025; 333:1722-723."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85719"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21651"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21911"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21911"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2Yikawp1mbu9ftxjQAyJRmg4W0ph8C.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2Yikawp1mbu9ftxjQAyJRmg4W0ph8C.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":261,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85719"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T12:39:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T20:39:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14520"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103300"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"